 to transnational social movements, women’s history, and religious studies, as she traces the connections between turn-of-the-century Christian women’s reform culture and liberal and left-wing religious social movements of the 1960s and 1970s. Izzo suggests that shared ethical, theological, and institutional underpinnings can transcend denominational divides, and that strategies for social change often associated with secular feminism have ties to spiritually inspired social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aYWCA.  acatholic.  acivil rights.  aprotestant.  asocial change.  asocial progress.  atraditional family.  awomen's history.  ayoung women's christian association.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106660830 cprintz978081358848340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813588506?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813588506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813588506/original  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK